<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="562" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1577,1818]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1577,1602]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Members of this subgenus may usually be recognized by the presence of supernumerary crossveins in both the clavus and corium of the forewing, the relatively long, slender aedeagus, and the medial posterior lobe of female abdominal sternite VII either absent or no wider than the lateral lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="562" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1577,1818]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1685,1710]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Remarks.</emphasis>
This subgenus is less well defined and more morphologically heterogeneous than 
<taxonomicName authority="Sinada &amp; Blocker. Most" authorityName="Sinada &amp; Blocker. Most" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Polyamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Copolyamia">
<emphasis box="[1329,1436,1685,1709]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Polyamia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[160,297,1722,1746]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Copolyamia</emphasis>
) Sinada &amp; Blocker. Most
</taxonomicName>
species occur in subtropical and tropical grasslands of 
<collectingRegion box="[1212,1298,1721,1746]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">
<collectingCountry box="[1212,1298,1721,1746]" name="Mexico" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
and Central America, although the 
<typeStatus box="[416,464,1758,1782]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Van Duzee" authorityName="Van Duzee" authorityYear="1892" box="[572,854,1757,1782]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Deltocephalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weedi" subGenus="Polyamia">
<emphasis box="[572,586,1758,1781]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">P</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[612,626,1758,1781]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">P</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[652,717,1757,1781]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">weedi</emphasis>
Van Duzee
</taxonomicName>
, illustrated below (
<figureCitation box="[1077,1181,1757,1782]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 7" captionStart-1="FIGURE 8" captionStartId-0="8.[151,250,869,891]" captionStartId-1="8.[151,250,1938,1960]" captionTargetBox-0="[171,1416,203,838]" captionTargetBox-1="[191,1375,949,1909]" captionTargetId-0="figure@8.[151,1436,193,848]" captionTargetId-1="figure@8.[169,1396,925,1926]" captionTargetPageId-0="8" captionTargetPageId-1="8" captionText-0="FIGURE 7. Polyamia (Polyamia) weedi A–B: habitus, dorsal view; C: habitus, lateral view; D: face." captionText-1="FIGURE 8. Polyamia (Polyamia) weedi A: male pygofer lobe, lateral view; B: male pygofer and segments X–XI, dorsal view; C: valve, subgenital plates and styles, ventral view; D: style, dorsal view; E, F: connective and aedeagus, dorsal and lateral view, respectively." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/1458055/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/1458057/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Figs 7–8</figureCitation>
), is widespread in the eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[237,297,1794,1818]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">USA</collectingCountry>
. Here we describe the first species of the subgenus (and genus) recorded from South America.
</paragraph>
